Overview

This example demonstrates how osm2hydro can be used. The OSM files for the globe or selected areas can be downloaded here: http://wiki.openstreetmap.org/wiki/Planet.osm

The following functionality is included:

  • Crop large osm file
  • Run osm2hydro and visualize
    • Convert osm file into a number of Shapefiles (see osm2shp.ini)
    • Convert resulting Shapefiles into a raster file
  • Analyze results
    • Compare results to the landuse maps (Corine, GBKN)

Crop OSM file and convert to binary (PBF)

This is just an example showing how to run shell command from the IPython Notebook. Extract OSM using \(envelope=lon_{min}, lat_{min}, lon_{max}, lat_{max}\) from the large OSM file, write results as a binary OSM file (Protobuf).

In [100]: 
!..\..\dist\win32\osmconvert.exe -b=5.9,51.965,6.1,52.03 arnhem.osm -o=output/arnhem_extract.pbf

Run osm2hydro

In [1]: 
from osm2hydro import osm2hydro
osm2hydro.main([('-c','osm2hydro.ini')])

Show results

# define function used to draw shapefile (move to utils)

xmin=5.89
xmax=6.02
ymin=51.955
ymax=52.03

def plot_shapefile(ax, path, c='b',a=1.0):
    import ogr
    import os
    shp = ogr.Open(path)

    l = shp.GetLayer(0)
    t = l.GetGeomType()

    verts = []
    if t == ogr.wkbPolygon:
        for f in shp.GetLayer(0):
            g = f.GetGeometryRef()
            g = g.GetGeometryRef(0)
            points = g.GetPoints()
            verts.append(points)
        polygons = matplotlib.collections.PolyCollection(verts, edgecolors='none')
        polygons.set_facecolor(c)
        polygons.set_alpha(a)
    elif t == ogr.wkbLineString:
        for f in shp.GetLayer(0):
            g = f.GetGeometryRef()
            points = g.GetPoints()
            verts.append(points)
        polygons = matplotlib.collections.PolyCollection(verts, edgecolors=c, closed=False)
        polygons.set_facecolor('w')
    else:
        raise Exception("Support for geometry type %d is not implemented yet" %fg.GetGeometryType())
        
    ax.add_collection(polygons)

    ax.ticklabel_format(style = 'sci', useOffset=False)
    ax.set_title(os.path.basename(path) + '(' + str(l.GetFeatureCount()) + ')')
    ax.set_xlim(xmin, xmax)
    ax.set_ylim(ymin, ymax)

# read spatial reference system parameters from shp
import ogr

path = r'output\arnhem\osmshapes\lu_buildings.shp'
shp = ogr.Open(path)
layer = shp.GetLayer()
print layer.GetFeatureCount()
crs = layer.GetSpatialRef().ExportToWkt()
    
# create an empty raster file
import gdal

# parameters
width = 240
height = 78 
resolution = (0.000833333333300, -0.000833333333300)
origin = (5.900000000000000,52.030000000000001)
geotransform = (origin[0], resolution[0], 0.0, origin[1], 0.0, resolution[1])

raster = gdal.GetDriverByName('GTiff')
path = 'test.tif'
ds = raster.Create(path, width, height, 1, gdal.GDT_Float32)
ds.SetProjection(crs)
ds.SetGeoTransform(geotransform)
ds.GetRasterBand(1).SetNoDataValue(0.0)
ds = None # close
